    <annotation>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="head">
                    <marginalia_text>It importeth a courtier, to speak &amp; write excellently: without all appearance of Affectation.</marginalia_text>
                </position>
            </language>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="EN">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
                    <marginalia_text>His speech, must be sensible, fine &amp; sententious; with a flowing facilitie: like the elegant &amp; 
                        gallant stile of Ca[e]sar, Tullie, Osorius, most eloquent, but most easie.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Julius Caesar"/>
                    <person name="Cicero"/>
                    <person name="John Osorius"/> <!--JG: Probably Harvey is meaning John Osorius, the Spanish preacher-->
                </position>
            </language>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>Nec intelligo, quid Homero magnificentius legere possim: nec quid Virgilio diuinius. 
                    Plurima su[n]t in Homero, quae in coelu[m] tolli; nihil in nostro, quod melius possit optari. Sadoletus.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Homer"/>
                    <person name="Virgil"/>
                    <person name="Jacopo Sadoleto"/>
                    <X-ref book_title="De liberis recte instituendis liber" language="LA" person="Jacopo Sadoleto" text="Plurima esse in Homero, quae in coelu[m] tolli; nihil in nostro, quod melius possit optari"/> <!--JG: See: https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=beDfGS4XvK0C&pg=PA110&lpg=PA110&dq=nihil+in+nostro,+quod+melius+possit+optari&source=bl&ots=nCptNLCufM&sig=VUV_0RCaQv-xTkPt2MWbb9Y4XMQ&hl=en&sa=X&ei=bdAsVZqJFdLLaLr5gIgF&ved=0CCMQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=nihil%20in%20nostro%2C%20quod%20melius%20possit%20optari&f=false-->
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>I do not understand, what more splendid I can read in Homer, nor what more divine in Virgil. "The greatest things are in
            Homer, which are lifted into heaven; [there is] nothing in ours, that can be chosen better". Sadoletus.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
